(37.6149283, -122.1056409).   Seen close to Black-bellied Plovers. Petite, much smaller head and shorter bill. Black-bellied Plovers are currently in various stages of molting, but this bird caught my attention first because of it's more golden tone.  It was moving around feeding, providing some nice comparisons to the Black-bellied Plovers.  Digiscoped.  My estimate is that this location is about midway between the two entry points to Eden Landing.  I would recommend starting on the north entry near the San Mateo Bridge for better shorebird viewing along the route.
Smaller and less bulky then nearby Black-bellied Plovers with thinner bill and golden cheeks.  Forgot my cell phone but a passerby was nice enough to let me use it to digi-scope

I was on the northern end of Frank's Dump when Sharon J. posted that she had refound it in the southwestern corner so I raced over there on my bike and got great looks at it as it was methodically working at the edge of the shoreline   When you get good looks the difference in bill length and shape from Western Sandpipers is clear.  Large white supercillium, very white chest but with slight buff streaking.   Enjoyed watching it with Bruce Mast's master birding class as they joined us. The bird stayed in that same area for quite a long time as Teale Fristoe got it there after we left.

Large white supercillium, very white chest but with slight buff streaking.   Enjoyed watching it with Bruce Mast's master birding class as they joined us. Medium size wader flew in and landed in the far shore of the small pond at Sindicich Lagoon (37.946004, -122.141930) while I was taking a short break on my mountain biking ride this morning at Briones Regional Park. The entire time it stayed along the small shore area giving decent views through the reeds.  When I first saw it I was thinking Lesser Yellowlegs but my hope quickly turned to Solitary Sandpiper it as its legs were dull greenish/yellow and it had a bold white eye-ring.  It some ways at quick glance it looks like a cross between a Lesser Yellowlegs and Spotted Sandpiper.  At one point a covey of California Quail came right down to the Solitary but it didn’t flinch.  I biked up from the main parking lot at Bear Creek Road, but Sindicich Lagoon is probably easier to get to from Briones Road Staging Area.  Photos

Ethan's find from yesterday continued, refound by Teale Fristoe around 11:30 am.  I arrived and after about 5 minutes or so it was picked up again.   Over the roughly two hour period I was there the large gull flock (2-3k) on the water was mostly fairly close to shore and easy to scan to pick up candidates for the Slaty. Shortly before I left suddenly all most all of the gulls moved further offshore, maybe in response to the outgoing tide, but even then they were still fairly easy to scan.  FYI, it's about .5 walk from the parking area to where the gulls tend to congregate.  Photos.

Originally reported by Charles Hargrove yesterday (at the time he didn't use the Lake Anza hotspot). See in the trees between the path and the lake on both sides of the spillway but mostly on the side that goes towards the swimming pool. After being on it for a while Rob Rafael and then Charles joined me in viewing it. No red on nape and malar stripe continuing as all-complete black border on the throat.   Pattern on back less definitive as there are two  whitish bands going down the back but in reviewing many photos of Yellow-bellied's in the eastern US (to avoid the potential hybrid issues in all photos taken out west) we see some that have a pattern similar pattern.

Locality: Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Continuing bird. Very active - watched for 15 minutes - fed in 8 trees - the red breasted sapsucker in my yard has only used 7 trees in 4 years of watching. Derek got pictures.   Where we found it - along East side of creek about .2 miles north of road - look back towards road and we saw the bird at the last spot you can still see the bridge over the creek.  Separate Red patches at throat, crown and nape - with two lines of white bars along back.  It’s been a while since I have seen a red-naked that is not an intergrade with a red-breasted....

Locality: Pescadero Creek Rd.-- Butano Creek riparian area
Observation Details: Continuing on either side of the stream well north of the road. Apparent pure Red-naped Sapsucker, though the white supercilium is extremely lacking.

Locality: Creekside Park (Brentwood, CC Co.) (includes Creek Rd)
Observation Details: Continuing bird found yesterday by Bruce Brown.  Seen flying out of the pepper trees next to the golf course pond,(37.9100365, -121.7151951) and it landed on a tree between the two paths for a few minutes before flying further across the drainage area where it actively moved around for a few minutes until we lost track of it.   I had spent over an hour looking in the same trees earlier in the day with no luck and the bird was seen not too long after I left, so I believe this bird could be just hanging  out in there for long periods of time.  There are multiple Red-breasted Sapsuckers in this same area, one that is active in those same pepper trees.

Seen at 7:10 this morning briefly in very poor light as light rain had just stopped falling.   Looking east from the bulb into the sun, I saw a kingbird at medium distance (37.890617, -122.323842)  whose giss felt Tropical, so I rushed over quickly for a better look. It was facing away, but with head turned the bill was obviously big and long.  I got a few poor photos before it was flushed and flew away and frustratingly could not be refound. I biked down to Cesar Chavez Park, checking all the logical spots with no luck and upon return back to Albany Bulb tried again and dipped. In looking at photos tail is also strongly notched.

Looking east from the bulb into the sun, I saw a kingbird at medium distance (37.890617, -122.323842)  whose giss felt Tropical, so I rushed over quickly for a better look. It was facing away, but with head turned the bill was obviously big and long.  I got a few poor photos before it was flushed and flew away and frustratingly could not be refound. In red berry tree where rbg grosbeaks seen. Derek got pictures. Then flew to euc above berry tree. Saw 4 or 5 times over 5-8 minutes. Loosely  warbling vireo.  Knew it wasn't a wRbling vireo as its back was yellowish-green with very grey hood with high contrast. Wanted to call it a red-eyed vireo but no contrast on face markings and eye not red. Got derek on bird and somehow he got picks. Picks seen by several (Oscar and Cedric) and called yellow green vireo. Also called out and Calvin had just arrived and his impression was Yellow green.  Absolutely amazing! Thought it was too windy but still went out and this was the reward.

Continuing nesting birds. Observed for about 40 minutes and during that time they were actively coming and going, sallying from the nesting pole providing nice looks, going into the nest hole, perching on top of the pole or occasionally a nearby structure.  At one point a few swallows came by and there was a little aerial warfare but nothing too serious.  During the time I was there they were not away for more than a few minutes before coming back.  Hope they find this location suitable for nesting next year too.  Rewarding looks after a bike ride up from home.

First one seen  high, high up at the top of a tall euc on Philips Trail at (37.8304161, -122.1779965).  Unfortunately it flew off and across the canyon. But not much further down the trail I saw at least two more at (37.8305059, -122.1773863) among quite a flurry of Hermit Thrushes and American Robins feeding on the toyon berries.  Grayish thrushes with white eye ring, buffy wing stripes and long tails. No vocalizations heard There could have been 3 or 4 Solitaires, but I only added 2 more to my checklist, sometimes perching together.  This area in Redwood Park has many berry-laden toyons so the solitaires could move around quite a bit.   On the same day last year Marsha Feinland and Alex Henry found a solitaire in the same vicinity that was seen by many through March 1 of this year. Hopefully at least a one of these will stay too.

Spotted small sparrow south of the lake at 37.9122730, -122.3868793.  Was obviously a spizella and I ruled out Clay-colored as the facial markings were not strong.  After two hours searching for it in that are Jack Hayden showed up and as I walked towards him the Brewer's flew in and landed less than five feet from where I originally spotted it and proceeded to feed on a small thistle for five or ten minutes allowing us to take photos. Very pale overall, not strong gray contrast on the nape led us to agree on Brewer's.  Noah Arthur showed up soon after and agreed  Photos attached.

Locality: Coyote Point County Park--harbor and marsh
Observation Details: Immature bird best views - in front of yacht club building - I hope Derek posts the The pictures  of this desert sparrow bathing. I did not realize these guys were so tiny until I saw this bird side by side with a junco and white throated sparrow - maybe 2/3 the size...  Supposed resident desert bird but I think desert birds disperse as they are alwAys dealing with droughts and that explains what this bird is in San Mateo - a young bird off course as pRt of a desert related natural dispersal.

Flew out from low in the coyote bush just left right inside the trailhead and landed on toyonal tree close by for a couple minutes.  When it first flew it appeared larger than the many House Finches but what caught my attention was the white wing patch.  The white chin and dark stripe visible while it perched.

Seen in the blackberry bramble from near the hanging feeder along the eastern side of Portola Way. Arrived and Pat Baccheti and Emilie Strauss were they and had seen it a few minutes earlier. Took maybe 20 minutes later into it popped up in the bramble. After a couple minutes it flew over to underneath the hanging feeder and foraging on the ground for a few minutes before flying back to the bramble, perching out in the open for a few minutes and then dove back out of sight back into the bramble. In flight white batches on wings clearly visible. Photos.

continuing at big the bridge midway on the east side, very skulky. Saw it immediately upon arrival for a fraction of a second and for the next fifteen minutes saw vegetation moving in an eight foot area right by the foot bridge but not a glimpse of the bird. Eventually it flew to the other side of the little channel and started showing itself in the reeds. During the entire time we were there (25 minutes-ish), it probably didn't get more than 12 feet from the foot bridge.  Medium size sparrow with clean underparts, rufous on wing, gray nape. Nice find Tom, taking the time to pick this out where it's easy to assume Song Sparrow.  Photos

Locality: Islay Creek Campground--Montana de Oro SP
Observation Details: First seen at 7:10 flying into the cacti.  Over the next 40 minutes it would move around in the cacti for a few minutes, then fly out to the riparian areas and come back a few minutes later for another round. Best views finally were at the lower end where it was feeding in the open.  Cacti are at 35.27480, -120.88636. It was definitely coming back a second time to get much improved views of this spectacular bird!  Photos.

We never saw the male, though other birders did before we arrived. We saw two female types, likely an adult and a juvenile, around 37.513347,-121.892507. please be careful if you visit this area, as it's likely the species breeds here.  This species was also found at this location in the summer of 2017. It hasn't been detected since, but it also appears that few birders visit in the appropriate season. There are only seven records of western bluebird from the location between May and August from 2018-2021, and only a single record of lazuli bunting from this time. Have blue grosbeaks been breeding right under our noses this whole time???
